{"@context":"http://iiif.io/api/presentation/3/context.json","id":"https://digbmc.github.io/pta-manifests/phan/phan-05518/manifest.json","type":"Manifest","label":{"none":["PHAN-05518"]},"metadata":[{"label":{"none":["Timestamp"]},"value":{"none":["0:55:18"]}},{"label":{"none":["Film"]},"value":{"none":["Phantom Thread"]}},{"label":{"none":["Creator"]},"value":{"none":["Paul Thomas Anderson"]}},{"label":{"none":["Distance"]},"value":{"none":["plan américain"]}},{"label":{"none":["Angle"]},"value":{"none":["high"]}},{"label":{"none":["Location"]},"value":{"none":["interior"]}},{"label":{"none":["Movement"]},"value":{"none":["mobile, handheld, tilt"]}},{"label":{"none":["Composition"]},"value":{"none":["three shot"]}}],"summary":{"none":["A woman takes off the dress of an unconscious woman."]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05518/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"homepage":[{"id":"PHAN-05518","type":"Text","format":"text/html","label":{"none":["Object homepage"]}}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05518/canvas/1","type":"Canvas","height":1080,"width":1920,"label":{"none":["PHAN-05518"]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05518/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05518/canvas/1/annopage-1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05518/canvas/1/annopage-1/anno-1","type":"Annotation","motivation":"painting","target":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05518/canvas/1","body":{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05518/tiles/full/1920,1080/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":1080,"width":1920,"service":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05518/tiles","type":"ImageService3","profile":"http://iiif.io/api/image/3/level0.json"}]}}]}],"annotations":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05518/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05518/canvas/1/96b8f050-66e1-4d67-83c5-70f59d34fc5a","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-30T14:03:47.345Z","creator":"Tallulah Stallvik","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>In an inversion of Alma’s first date with Reynolds, she is now the one undressing a woman. Reynolds’s admiration for Alma only grows as she takes on certain of his characteristics and passions.</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05518/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:914.3484805045873,274.54128440366975,554.0495986238532,610.4092603211009"}}},{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05518/canvas/1/223c2a66-2355-4c50-9b1f-0bb028d2239b","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-30T14:04:17.828Z","creator":"Tallulah Stallvik","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>The conventions of the wedding night are subverted in this scene, emphasizing the absence of care from Barbara’s husband. She was carried across the threshold to her room, as is the custom, but not by her husband. Instead, a large group was required to carry her body into the room, as she had passed out from drunkenness. Her dress—already not traditional white—is removed by Alma, rather than her husband. While the scene carries some clear erotic undertones, they only serve to emphasize the lack of actual erotics in the scene, and Barbara’s relationship at large. The person bent over her, removing her dress, is not her husand but Alma, and her groans as it is taken off are not of pleasure, but sounds of discomfort in her drunken slumber. On her wedding night, Barbara is ultimately left lonely and unfulfilled.&nbsp;</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-05518/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:29.283258439757347,32.7270474892385,271.14392201834875,216.7574541284405"}}}]}]}]}